		<table width="90%" bgcolor="" style="border-collapse: collapse; border-left-width:1; border-right-width: 1; border-top-style: solid; border-left-style: solid; border-right-style: solid; border-bottom-style: solid; border-top-width: 1; border-bottom-width: 1" bordercolor="#FFFFFF" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" ID="Table2">  
		<tr>
			<td align="left" valign="top" background="/images/necrotableheader2.gif">
				<font width="100%" face="verdana" size="1" color=white><b>Soloing In The Katta Castellum Graveyard [Post Pathing Patch]</b>
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr bgcolor="#ffebdc">
			<td align="left" valign="top" valign="top">
				<font face="verdana" size="1" color=white>
				written by <b>Xenith112</b> on <b>6/9/2003 12:23:05 PM</b>
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr bgcolor="#37437B">
			<td align="left" valign="top" valign="top">
				<font face="verdana" size="1" color=white><blockquote><br>
				As you may all well know, the last major update patch truly screwed over alot of pathing, and one of the most drastically effected places was Katta.  Nowadays, if you try fear kiting in the courtyard, you must be looking for some sort of deathwish, as the single feared guard will aggro the entire plaza on to you.  Looks like SOE decided to make this zone into a Wizard and Druid playground.<br><br>Fear not, though, as you can still effectively solo in here, but instead of fear kiting, you'll be doing it the Druid way.  <br><br>Here is what I recommend you have memmed:<br><br>Feign Death<br>Invoke Fear (In case the mob is attacking you and your low on health. Do this only when your deeply in the graveyard and make sure the mob is snared before casting.)<br>Envenomed Bolt<br>Splurt<br>Vexing of Mord. (Or Bond of Death if your are not yet lvl 57.)<br>Pyrocur (Or Ignite Blood if you don't have it yet.)<br>Dooming Darkness<br>Instill<br><br>Buffs:<br><br>Health Buffs (Blessing of Aegolism, Virtue, PoTG, etc, but not required at all...just helps your liching abilities.)<br>SoW or JBoots (Either grab the boots or grab a few stacks of sow potions, these will lessen the chances a mob will hit you.)<br><br>First, set up your camp in the Graveyard, and park your pet there.  Being a Necromancer, the undead mobs won't bother you.  All you have to do to all of these mobs is the following: Snare, run back a few steps, hit the mob with Splurt, then run back into the graveyard and hit him with Evenomened Bolt, then ROOT the mob into place. Then either hit the mob with a lifetap dot depending on your health or just finish the combo with your poisen dot.  <br><br>Your root is guranteed to break once the mob's hp is around the 20-30% range,  Don't bother recasting your root on it, instead, just renew Dooming Darkness and have your pet get onto him.  Once the mob's hp is below 20%, he will start running away.  Usually, the pet will finish him off before he gets too far away, but if you think he's going to get out of the graveyard, root him.  This will make him turn around and start attacking your pet, but it's better than having 2 more mobs aggroed on to you.<br><br>The only two mobs that could pose a problem is the ones on the right that are bunched together.  Those mobs will aggro together if your not 56 or higher (I still had the other one aggro about once every 5 times I pulled one at 56, though, so be prepared.) so your going to have to do a bit of FD pulling.  Snare the closest one, then run back into the graveyard where your parked pet is.  When your inside, Feign Death.  If it fails, get up immediatly and activate your JBoots and run around in circles until you can FD again.  When it succeeds, wait until the unsnared guard walks back to his post, then root the snared guard and repeat the dot process on him.  You don't have to use your pet at all, but its nice to have them around when things get a bit out of hand.  Thats basically it, just watch out for the wandering mob that paths through the courtyard.  Kill him before you aggro any other mobs, or your gonna have a add.<br><br>- Numnaydar, 58th Season Defiler of Innoruuk<br>- Quellious<br>&nbsp;<br>
			</td>
		</tr>
